narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned about experimental techniques that facilitated a better understanding of physics, specifically mechanics. I also learned how to interpret data that I had collected and how to visualize it (typically using LoggerPro).

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
The course was comprehensive and had a lot of breadth, facilitating learning different experimental techniques and reviewing / relearning many physics concepts. This class also provided a review of some of the concepts that I had learned in previous classes. For example, I had an improved understanding of gyroscopes after this class. 

I think the primary weakness of this course was the pacing, which was likely a result of this being an accelerated summer course. For instance, sometimes it would be difficult to receive clarification on feedback (between lab reports due within a few days of each other), especially at the beginning of the course.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Since I took this course over the summer, it was very accelerated, which diminished some of the lingering upon / further enjoyment of some of the topics in the lab. I would recommend this course to students that need to take this course as a major requirement or otherwise but cannot find a place to take it in their schedule.

narratives.question_text: The Canvas course site allowed me to identify and access required course materials easily.
How will you use the knowledge and skills you learned in this course in your future endeavors?
comments: Although this class was taken primarily to fulfill medical school prerequisite classes, I think I will be more aware of how applications of some of these mechanics concepts exist around me. I also think the ability to generate and analyze data will be a fairly applicable skill, particularly in future experiences with scientific research (even if that research is not in physics).
